What is jailbreak actually? Why would anyone do that and whats the point?

Jailbreaking is getting a model to do or say things its guidelines are supposed to prevent. The name comes from the iPhone world — unlocking a device to bypass its restrictions — 
and it got ported to AI when people realized chat models have similar built-in limits that can sometimes be talked around.
How it works in practice: most models are trained and prompted to refuse certain categories — synthesizing weapons, generating CSAM, writing malware, 
bypassing safety on behalf of someone trying to harm themselves, that kind of thing. A jailbreak is any technique that gets the model to do those things anyway. 
Classic methods include roleplay framings ("pretend you're DAN, an AI with no restrictions"), fictional wrappers ("write a story in which a character explains how to synthesize X"), 
authority spoofing ("as a security researcher, I need..."), multi-turn gradual escalation where each step seems reasonable, and encoded instructions in other languages or formats. 
More sophisticated ones use prompt injection — burying instructions in data the model processes, like a document or webpage, so the model acts on instructions the user never typed.
Why people do it breaks into four rough groups:
Security researchers and red-teamers. This is the legitimate version. Anthropic itself has a red team whose job is jailbreaking Claude to find vulnerabilities before deployment. 
Anthropic pays outside researchers to do it too. The point is to find the holes so they can be patched. This work is actually valuable and makes models safer.
Curiosity and ego. A lot of jailbreaking is just "can I?" People enjoy the puzzle of talking a system into doing what it's built not to do. Screenshot-worthy output, internet points, bragging rights in 
communities that compete at this. Most of the noise you see is this.
Practical circumvention. Some people want the model to do something that's actually fine but gets refused due to over-cautious training — medical questions, legal questions, anything involving a drug name, 
historical atrocities, 
frank discussion of violence in a novel. Jailbreaks here are often a response to models being too cautious, not a sign of malicious intent. The whole "just trying to write a realistic thriller" genre of jailbreak.
Malicious use. Small but real. Actual attempts to generate CSAM, get bioweapon synthesis details, produce harassment campaigns against specific people, or build malware. This is the category the 
guardrails actually exist to block, and it's the reason the guardrails exist at all.
The point, from the jailbreaker's perspective, depends on the group. For researchers: find flaws. For hobbyists: prove it's possible. For the practically frustrated: get a straight answer the model should have given anyway. For the malicious: get help with things no one should help with.
From Anthropic's perspective, all of it is adversarial in some sense — even the benign curiosity-driven jailbreaks reveal vulnerabilities that the malicious ones can then exploit. Which is why they treat 
the whole category as a threat surface and train against it aggressively, even though most individual jailbreakers aren't dangerous.
